{
  "doc_id": "53966",
  "text": "Interestingly, during S. pneumoniae infection of alveolar epithelial cells, we observed two patterns of γH2AX staining depending on the MOI used. Low MOI (30-50) yielded foci of γH2AX with 53BP1 in almost half of the total γH2AX-positive population, whereas the other half portrayed pan-γH2AX phosphorylation without any 53BP1 staining. At higher MOI (200-400), only pan-γH2AX staining without 53BP1 was observed. During infection of animals, we observed that pan-γH2AX constituted about 30% of the total γH2AX analyzed in the lung sections (Fig. S10) . The pan-γH2AX staining has been reported to occur in human fibroblast cells subjected to Adeno-associated virus [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , Chlamydia (33), and UV and ionizing radiation [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Recently, such nuclear-wide γH2AX has been shown to occur in highly DNAdamaged cells and is mediated by ATM kinase [CITATION_6] . Here, we found that most of the pan-γH2AX phosphorylation was dependent on ATM kinase and hence constituted part of the DNA damage response cascade induced by S. pneumoniae.",
